# SEQUENCE I — THE LAST MORNING

FADE IN:

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - PRE-DAWN

A kettle begins to whistle.

No one comes.

The television murmurs morning news into an empty living room.

A hallway lamp burns against the first grey suggestion of daylight.

The house has continued without permission.

At the entrance:

A polished pair of shoes.
A carved walking stick.
Prayer beads looped carefully over the handle.

In the living room:

ACHEBE beside SOYINKA.
An EFIK BIBLE with a repaired spine.
Canadian immigration manuals, decades out of date.
A carved brass leopard on a tray darkened by fingerprints.
Family photographs arranged with almost obsessive care.

One frame hangs crooked.

The only one.

In the kitchen:

Gari. Crayfish. Maggi.
Peak Milk. Ovaltine.
Three mustard jars in the refrigerator door.
One thriving plant on the windowsill.
Two dead ones beside it.

The kettle SCREAMS.

The front door opens.

MALIK OKU, 36, enters in funeral black beneath a winter coat.

He carries three coffees, garment bags, black garbage sacks and a folder thick with documents.

He closes the door with his heel.

Sees the kettle.

Crosses quickly.

Switches it off.

Silence rushes back in.

Malik checks the stove.

All four burners.

He switches off the television.

Then the hallway lamp.

He sets the coffees on the counter in a straight line.

Not straight enough.

He adjusts them.

He notices a dish towel hanging unevenly from the oven handle.

Removes it.

Folds it into exact thirds.

Places it down.

A beat.

He moves it half an inch to the left.

The front door opens behind him.

ADE OKU, 32, enters carrying his dress shoes and wearing his tie around his neck like a surrender flag.

He watches Malik wipe an already-clean patch of counter.

ADE
You know they sell those pre-cleaned.

Malik keeps wiping.

MALIK
You said six-thirty.

ADE
I meant emotionally.

Malik checks the wall clock.

6:41.

Then his watch.

Then the wall clock again.

ADE
Vancouver's running behind.

Ade takes the coffee at the end of the row.

Malik moves the remaining two closer together.

Ade notices.

Says nothing.

He opens the refrigerator.

Yellow mustard.
Dijon.
Grainy.

Ade stares at the grainy mustard.

A memory tries to happen.

He closes the refrigerator before it can.

MALIK
You need to change.

ADE
This is black.

MALIK
Those are sweatpants.

ADE
Grief has lowered its standards.

Malik removes a loose thread from Ade's coat sleeve.

Ade lets him.

The front door opens again.

KAI OKU, 25, enters with a digital camera against his chest and noise-cancelling headphones around his neck.

He stops inside the doorway.

Does not greet either brother.

Listens.

The refrigerator hum.
Pipes settling.
A neighbour's car starting outside.
The faint electrical buzz of the hallway lamp Malik switched off.

Kai looks toward the staircase.

Nothing.

He removes his headphones.

KAI
The clock's wrong.

Malik looks at the wall clock.

MALIK
It is not.

Kai points.

The second hand hesitates at twelve.

Moves.

Hesitates again.

KAI
It loses one second every minute.

ADE
Dad bought it at a gas station.

KAI
He hated losing time.

Malik takes the clock from the wall.

Removes the battery.

The ticking stops.

Kai watches him set it face-down on the counter.

An interrupted pattern.

Malik moves away.

Kai turns the clock face-up.

Near Solomon's chair sits an old CAMCORDER.

Scratched casing.

A strip of masking tape underneath:

SOLOMON.

Kai picks it up.

Presses POWER.

Nothing.

He opens the battery compartment.

Empty.

KAI
Where's the battery?

MALIK
Leave it.

KAI
He kept them in the blue drawer.

Kai crosses to a narrow drawer beside the telephone.

Opens it.

Rubber bands.
Receipts.
A tiny screwdriver.
Three dead pens.

No battery.

He searches beneath the receipts.

MALIK
Kai.

Kai closes the drawer.

Then opens it again.

ADE
Maybe it achieved freedom.

Kai keeps searching.

ADE
The battery. Not Dad.

No one moves.

Ade looks down.

The joke has failed to restart the room.

Kai removes every object from the drawer and arranges them on the counter.

Rubber bands together.
Pens parallel.
Receipts by size.

One receipt is folded around something hard.

Kai opens it.

A small BRASS CARVING.

Too worn to identify clearly.

Animal.
Mask.
Both.

Kai turns it beneath the kitchen light.

MALIK
Put it back.

KAI
What is it?

MALIK
Something he kept.

KAI
That isn't an answer.

MALIK
It is this morning.

Kai studies Malik.

Places the carving back inside the receipt.

But not in the drawer.

Beside the camcorder.

Malik picks it up.

Returns it to the drawer.

Closes the drawer firmly.

Kai's eyes move to the crooked photograph in the living room.

He crosses to it.

The photograph shows the three brothers as children beside Solomon.

Malik rigid in a suit too large for him.
Ade caught halfway through saying something.
Kai small enough to be held.

Solomon looks directly at the camera.

Not smiling.

The frame leans slightly left.

Kai straightens it.

Steps back.

Something is wrong.

He tilts it crooked again.

The image settles.

KAI
He did that on purpose.

MALIK
Did what?

KAI
Left it wrong.

ADE
Maybe he was testing whether Malik could feel joy.

Malik lifts the garment bags.

MALIK
Get dressed.

Kai remains at the photograph.

On a lower shelf, an empty rectangle interrupts a line of dust.

Something used to sit there.

KAI
What's missing?

Malik does not look.

MALIK
Nothing.

KAI
There was something here.

ADE
Kai.

KAI
The dust is different.

Malik checks his folder.

Passports.
Funeral paperwork.
Three printed schedules.

MALIK
We are leaving in twelve minutes.

ADE
He made an agenda for Dad's burial.

MALIK
Someone had to.

ADE
Yeah.

Too fast.

Too sharp.

Malik looks at him.

Ade softens it.

ADE
I mean, imagine the chaos otherwise. People grieving without assigned seating.

Malik aligns the folder with the counter's edge.

ADE
There he is.

MALIK
Who?

ADE
Nobody.

Ade takes the garment bags from him.

For one brief moment, Malik has nothing in his hands.

He looks toward the staircase.

At the dark landing above.

A floorboard CREAKS.

All three brothers look up.

Nothing moves.

The house waiting for a man who will not come downstairs.

Kai raises his camera.

Not to film.

To frame.

Through the viewfinder:

The empty staircase.
The crooked photograph.
Malik reflected in the brass tray.
Ade holding Solomon's garment bag against his chest.

A tiny BLACK SPIDER crosses the upper corner of the frame.

Kai lowers the camera.

Looks directly.

Nothing there.

MALIK
What?

KAI
Nothing.

Malik takes Solomon's urn from the dining table.

BRASS.
Polished.
A faint thumbprint near the lid.

Malik sees it.

Wipes it away with his sleeve.

The mark remains.

He wipes harder.

ADE
Malik.

Malik stops.

Ade holds out his hand for the urn.

Malik does not give it to him.

Kai switches off the kitchen light.

The room darkens except for dawn at the window.

For a moment, the brass carving inside the closed drawer catches a line of light through the narrow gap.

Then darkness.

The brothers leave.

The front door closes.

Silence.

The television switches on by itself.

Morning news murmurs to the empty house.

On the counter, the wall clock lies face-up without its battery.

Its second hand moves once.

CUT TO:

# SEQUENCE II — THE FUNERAL

EXT. MOUNTAIN VIEW CEMETERY – MORNING

Grey clouds press low over the Fraser Valley.

Rows of umbrellas.
Black coats.
Muted conversations.

The wind carries the smell of wet cedar and freshly turned earth.

At the centre—

SOLOMON OKU'S CASKET.

Covered with white lilies.

The brass urn rests beside it.

MALIK stands nearest the casket.

Still.
Hands clasped.

His funeral programme has already been folded into perfect quarters.

ADE lingers one row behind.

Shakes hands.
Accepts condolences.

Forgets every name the instant he hears it.

KAI remains apart.

Camera hanging unused.

Watching.

Always watching.

The PRIEST finishes the final prayer.

PRIEST
Ashes to ashes...
Dust to dust...

Silence.

Long enough to become uncomfortable.

A baby cries somewhere behind the mourners.

Someone clears their throat.

No one moves.

The funeral director nods gently.

DIRECTOR
Family first.

Malik steps forward.

Places one hand on the casket.

Not dramatic.

Practical.

As though confirming its weight.

Ade joins him.

Kai hesitates.

Then completes the line.

Together—

They guide the casket toward the lowering straps.

Metal creaks.

Leather tightens.

The casket begins its descent.

Halfway down—

A violent SCREECH erupts from nearby speakers.

Microphone feedback.

Sharp.
Unexpected.

Everyone flinches.

Everyone—

Except Kai.

His eyes are fixed somewhere else.

The sound seems distant.

Filtered.

He slowly turns.

Toward a line of cedar trees.

The branches move.

Nothing else.

The feedback stops.

Reality resumes.

Mourners laugh nervously.

The priest apologizes.

PRIEST
Sorry...
Technical difficulties.

Kai continues looking.

Something felt wrong.

Not seen.

Felt.

Ade notices.

ADE
Kai.

Kai blinks.

Returns.

As though surfacing.

The ceremony continues.

People begin placing flowers.

One by one.

Malik steps back.

Adjusts the folded programme in his pocket.

It is no longer square.

He removes it.

Refolds it.

Perfectly.

A MAN approaches.

Late fifties.

Tailored charcoal overcoat.

Umbrella closed despite the rain.

His shoes are wet.

He doesn't appear to notice.

BODE OKU.

He stops before the brothers.

No embrace.

No performance.

Only presence.

BODE
I'm sorry.

Malik nods.

Ade forces a smile that doesn't survive.

Kai studies him.

Bode looks toward Solomon's casket.

Then toward the brass urn.

His expression changes almost imperceptibly.

Recognition.

Or concern.

Impossible to tell.

BODE
Was it peaceful?

Malik answers.

MALIK
Yes.

A lie told kindly.

Bode accepts it.

No further questions.

He removes his gloves.

Places one hand gently on the casket.

Closes his eyes.

Just for a moment.

Then—

BODE
He hated being late.

Ade laughs.

One short breath.

Unexpected.

Then immediately feels guilty for it.

Bode hears it.

Smiles faintly.

BODE
He'd have complained about the weather.

ADE
He complained about every weather.

The smallest ripple of life passes through the brothers.

Gone almost immediately.

Workers begin lowering the casket fully.

The ropes slide.

Steady.

Controlled.

No music.

Only the sound of leather moving across metal.

Kai watches the casket disappear.

Not grieving.

Calculating.

Remembering.

Pattern after pattern.

Until—

He notices something.

The brass urn.

Its polished surface reflects the cedar trees.

For just an instant—

One reflection seems delayed.

Kai looks directly at the trees.

Nothing.

Looks back.

Only rain.

Only brass.

Only grief.

He says nothing.

Not yet.

The mourners begin to drift away.

Umbrellas bloom.

Condolences dissolve into practical conversations.

Cars start.

Doors slam.

Life resumes around grief.

Malik remains where he is.

Watching workers finish.

Checking every movement.

Every rope.

Every knot.

Every signature.

As though one mistake could still be prevented.

The cemetery slowly empties.

Only the brothers...

...and Bode remain.

The brass urn rests on a folding table beneath a small canopy.

Rain taps softly against its polished lid.

The FUNERAL DIRECTOR approaches.

DIRECTOR
Whenever you're ready.

Malik nods.

He reaches for the urn.

Stops.

His hand trembles.

Barely.

ADE notices.

Pretends he doesn't.

BODE quietly steps beside Malik.

Not in front of him.

Beside him.

BODE
You don't have to carry everything yourself.

Malik keeps looking at the urn.

MALIK
I'm trying.

Silence.

Then—

MALIK
I'm trying not to make another mistake for him.

No one answers immediately.

Rain fills the space.

Bode studies his nephew.

Not with pity.

Recognition.

BODE
Then let us carry him together.

He places one hand beneath the urn.

Waits.

Doesn't take it.

Waits.

Ade steps forward.

Supports the opposite side.

Kai hesitates.

Watching.

Calculating.

Then places both hands beneath the base.

Finally—

Malik releases just enough.

All four now carry Solomon.

Together.

No single person bears the weight.

They walk slowly toward the columbarium.

No music.

Only shoes against wet concrete.

The urn reflects them.

Four figures.

One family.

Ahead—

Rows of polished stone.

Hundreds of names.

Hundreds of lives reduced to dates.

The attendant unlocks a niche.

Steps away.

Giving them privacy.

The brothers stand before the opening.

No one knows who should move first.

Ade clears his throat.

Nothing comes.

Kai stares into the empty niche.

It feels...

Prepared.

Waiting.

Bode nods once.

Together—

They slide the urn into place.

The brass disappears into shadow.

The stone panel is lifted.

Bolts tightened.

Metal against granite.

Each turn of the wrench sounds louder than it should.

When the final bolt locks—

Silence.

Complete.

Kai looks toward the far end of the corridor.

Someone stands there.

Still.

Watching.

Too far away to identify.

Kai blinks.

The corridor is empty.

He turns back.

A faint...

TAP.

From inside the stone.

No one reacts.

Except Kai.

He doesn't move.

Doesn't speak.

He simply listens.

CUT TO BLACK.

# SEQUENCE III — THE WAKE

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE – EVENING

The front door opens.

The brothers enter.

No one speaks.

The house feels different.

Not haunted.

Occupied.

Malik removes his shoes.

Places them beside Solomon's.

Stops.

Realizes what he's done.

Moves his shoes further away.

Ade watches.

Says nothing.

Kai lingers in the doorway.

Listening.

The refrigerator hum.

Water inside old pipes.

A branch scraping the roof.

Then—

Nothing.

The silence has changed.

BODE enters last.

He closes the door gently.

BODE
Funerals are noisy.

No one answers.

BODE (CONT'D)
The quiet starts afterwards.

He removes his coat.

Looks around.

Nothing has changed.

Everything has.

Malik heads straight for the kitchen.

Instinct.

The sink.

The kettle.

The folded dish towel.

Everything exactly where he left it.

Except—

The towel.

Folded differently.

Malik freezes.

He unfolds it.

Refolds it into thirds.

Exactly.

He places it back.

Satisfied.

Turns.

The towel slips from the handle.

Falls to the floor.

No one touched it.

Ade sees Malik staring.

ADE
You okay?

Malik bends.

Picks it up immediately.

MALIK
Humidity.

Even he doesn't believe it.

Kai has wandered into the living room.

His camera hangs at his side.

He studies the shelf beneath the family photograph.

The empty rectangle in the dust.

Still empty.

He raises the camera.

Looks through the viewfinder.

The room becomes flatter.

Quieter.

The missing space appears...

Darker.

As though something still occupies it.

Kai lowers the camera.

Nothing.

He raises it again.

Normal.

Lowers it.

Normal.

He doesn't understand.

Not yet.

From the dining room—

Voices.

Neighbours arrive carrying food.

Metal trays.

Foil-covered dishes.

Rice.

Soup.

Stew.

Bread.

The familiar choreography of mourning.

Everyone knows where to stand.

No one knows what to say.

AUNTIE ENO enters.

Late sixties.

Strong.

Elegant.

She doesn't announce herself.

She belongs here.

She embraces Malik first.

Then Ade.

Then Kai.

Holding him longer.

ENO
Have you eaten?

Three different answers.

MALIK
Not yet.

ADE
Twice.

KAI
I don't know.

Eno nods.

All three answers make sense.

She walks into Solomon's kitchen.

Stops.

Looks at the mustard jars.

The dead plants.

The folded towel.

Her eyes settle on Solomon's chair.

Empty.

She quietly touches its back.

Not sentiment.

Recognition.

Without turning—

ENO
Who moved his things?

Silence.

The brothers exchange looks.

KAI
What things?

Eno gestures toward the shelf.

ENO
The carving.

Kai's attention sharpens.

Malik looks away.

ADE
There wasn't—

ENO
There was.

She studies each nephew.

One by one.

ENO (CONT'D)
Your father never left that shelf empty.

Kai looks toward the dust rectangle.

Then toward Malik.

Malik says nothing.

Outside—

Wind.

The lights flicker once.

Everyone notices.

No one comments.

The power steadies.

Conversation resumes.

Only Kai continues watching the hallway.

At the end of it—

The staircase.

Empty.

Above—

A single floorboard CREAKS.

Not loud.

Not threatening.

Just enough.

Kai raises the camera.

Frames the staircase.

Through the viewfinder—

A black spider waits on the banister.

Perfectly still.

Kai lowers the camera.

Nothing.

Raises it again.

The spider is gone.

CUT TO:

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - DINING ROOM - LATER

The wake has found its volume.

Condolences overlap.

Cutlery touches china.

Wet coats surrender their rain to the hardwood.

Every flat surface has become useful.

Foil trays of jollof rice.

Moi moi unwrapped from broad green leaves.

Meat pies beneath a tea towel.

A deep enamel pot of AFANG SOUP that belongs unmistakably to Eno.

People eat because refusing would create another conversation.

Malik moves through the room collecting abandoned cups.

One in each hand.

Then two more balanced against his wrist.

If he keeps moving, no one can stop him.

At the front door, Ade receives a condolence from a WOMAN who has already given it twice.

WOMAN
Your father was a good man.

ADE
Thank you.

WOMAN
A very private man.

ADE
That too.

She squeezes his hand.

ADE
If you remember anything embarrassing,
we're taking those in the kitchen.

The woman laughs.

Ade smiles with her.

She moves on.

The smile leaves before she does.

Kai sits at the edge of the staircase.

Camera in his lap.

He scrolls backward through the footage.

The staircase.

Empty.

The banister.

Empty.

Frame by frame.

Nothing.

He reaches the instant before the spider appeared.

The image breaks into a brief mosaic of black squares.

One frame.

Then clean again.

Kai goes back.

The black squares are gone.

A COUSIN leans over him with a plate.

COUSIN
You no dey eat?

Kai covers the screen with his hand.

KAI
I'm not hungry.

COUSIN
Nobody asked whether you are hungry.

She puts the plate beside him.

COUSIN (CONT'D)
Eat small.

She leaves.

Kai looks at the food.

Doesn't touch it.

Across the room, Eno watches him.

Then the kitchen.

Then the shelf beneath the family photograph.

The empty rectangle in the dust.

She moves.

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - KITCHEN - CONTINUOUS

Malik rinses cups as quickly as people can abandon them.

Eno enters.

She turns off the tap.

Malik turns it back on.

Eno turns it off again.

ENO
The cups will survive.

MALIK
There aren't enough.

ENO
There have never been enough cups
at a funeral.

She opens a narrow drawer beside the telephone.

The blue drawer.

Rubber bands.

Receipts.

Three dead pens.

The tiny screwdriver.

Eno moves each object without disturbing its position.

Her fingers stop.

A receipt folded around something hard.

She lifts it.

The room seems to lose one degree of warmth.

Malik sees her expression.

MALIK
What?

Eno unfolds the receipt.

The small BRASS CARVING.

Animal.

Mask.

Both.

ENO
Who put this here?

Kai stands in the doorway.

He has followed without being noticed.

KAI
It was already there.

Eno looks at him.

KAI (CONT'D)
I found it this morning.

MALIK
And I put it back.

ENO
Back?

MALIK
Where he kept it.

ENO
No.

Not sharp.

Certain.

ENO (CONT'D)
This is where he hid it.

Bode appears behind Kai.

He sees the carving.

Stops.

Not surprise.

Confirmation.

ADE (O.S.)
Why did the whole kitchen just become
a private meeting?

Ade joins them.

Looks from face to face.

Then the brass.

ADE (CONT'D)
Ah.

A haunted paperweight.

Nobody laughs.

Ade's expression changes.

ADE (CONT'D)
Okay.

Bode takes the edges of the receipt.

Never the carving.

BODE
Who touched it?

Kai raises a hand halfway.

KAI
I did.

Bode examines Kai's fingers.

The palm.

The wrist.

KAI
It didn't cut me.

BODE
I didn't ask whether it cut you.

That lands.

Bode realizes how it sounded.

Softens.

BODE (CONT'D)
Did it feel warm?

Kai thinks.

KAI
Everything in here feels warm.

ENO
Solomon took it from the shelf before
he went into hospital.

Malik looks toward the empty rectangle.

MALIK
Why?

Bode folds the receipt around the carving.

BODE
I don't know.

ADE
You looked very fluent in it for a man
who doesn't know.

BODE
I know what it is.

ADE
Wonderful.

BODE
I do not know why he moved it.

ADE
Less wonderful.

Eno reaches for the bundle.

Bode holds it away.

ENO
Don't start protecting him now.

BODE
I am protecting his sons.

MALIK
From what?

Before Bode can answer—

A burst of laughter from the dining room.

Too loud.

Too alive.

The four of them look toward it.

The wake continuing without permission.

Bode lowers his voice.

BODE
Your father deserves one evening
in which he is not turned into evidence.

Malik absorbs the rebuke.

Kai does not.

He watches Bode refold the receipt.

A white corner protrudes from beneath the brass.

Not paper.

Photographic stock.

KAI
Wait.

He reaches.

Bode moves too late.

Kai pulls free a small, creased PHOTOGRAPH.

Faded colour.

Humidity damage around the edges.

Four young people stand before a white house under a massive tree.

SOLOMON.

BODE.

ENO.

And a YOUNG WOMAN whose face has been scratched away.

Not crossed out.

Excavated.

Deep enough to expose the white beneath the image.

On the back, in Solomon's handwriting:

CALABAR. 1989.

Kai turns it over again.

The missing face seems brighter than every face around it.

KAI
Who did this?

Eno looks at the photograph.

Thirty-seven years pass through her before she answers.

ENO
Someone your father loved badly.

BODE
Eno.

She doesn't apologize.

ADE
That's not an answer.

ENO
It is the only one I have.

Malik takes the photograph from Kai.

Studies the house.

The tree.

The damaged woman.

MALIK
Where in Calabar?

BODE
Outside the city.

MALIK
Whose house?

Bode looks at Solomon in the photograph.

BODE
Your father's.

MALIK
Dad didn't own a house in Nigeria.

ENO
He owned many things he did not know
how to live with.

Malik turns to Bode.

MALIK
Is that what this is?

He holds up the photograph.

MALIK (CONT'D)
Another thing everybody knew except us?

Bode accepts the anger.

Does not defend himself from it.

BODE
Yes.

The honesty disarms Malik more than an excuse would.

From the dining room—

WOMAN (O.S.)
Eno! Come and see who has arrived.

Eno takes the photograph.

Bode catches her wrist.

Not forceful.

Old reflex.

They look at each other.

An argument older than the brothers passes silently between them.

Eno releases the photograph.

Leaves.

Bode places the carving and photograph inside the drawer.

Malik stops him from closing it.

MALIK
No.

Bode waits.

Malik removes the photograph.

Sets it on the counter.

Face-up.

The damaged woman among them.

MALIK (CONT'D)
No more putting things back because
they make everybody uncomfortable.

Ade looks at him.

For the first time all evening—

Malik is not cleaning.

He is making a mess.

CUT TO:

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - LIVING ROOM - NIGHT

The wake has thinned.

The last guests collect coats and foil-wrapped leftovers.

An auntie presses food into Malik's hands.

AUNTIE
Put it in freezer.

MALIK
There's no room.

AUNTIE
Then make room.

She leaves before he can refuse.

The door closes.

Quiet returns in layers.

First the voices disappear.

Then the engines outside.

Then the house begins making its own sounds again.

Bode stands at the window.

Eno wraps her pot in a dish towel.

Ade sinks into Solomon's chair.

Immediately stands again.

No one comments.

Kai sits on the floor beside the old camcorder.

The scratched photograph lies on the coffee table.

Malik remains standing.

MALIK
What happens tomorrow?

BODE
Nine o'clock.

MALIK
That is a time.

BODE
Your father's lawyer is coming.

ADE
To tell us what?

BODE
What he left.

Ade looks around the room.

ADE
Feels like we're standing in it.

BODE
This house is not the inheritance.

The brothers look at him.

Bode regrets saying even that much.

MALIK
Then what is?

BODE
Something Solomon should have explained
while he was alive.

ADE
He was saving a lot for the sequel.

The joke reaches no one.

Ade looks down.

The room is officially in danger.

MALIK
You could have told us before the funeral.

BODE
Before the funeral, you were carrying
your father.

MALIK
And now?

BODE
Now you can decide whether you want
to carry what belonged to him.

Malik glances toward the scratched photograph.

KAI
Does it have something to do with her?

Bode follows his gaze.

BODE
Everything has something to do with
someone.

ENO
Bode.

A warning.

Bode nods.

Tries again.

BODE
I don't know.

This time, they believe him.

Eno lifts her pot.

Stops beside Kai.

ENO
Eat before you sleep.

KAI
I'm not tired.

ENO
That is not what I said.

She kisses the top of his head.

At the door, she turns to Bode.

ENO (CONT'D)
Don't leave them with only half.

BODE
Half is all Solomon left me.

Eno considers that.

Then leaves.

The front door closes.

Kai looks at the old camcorder beside him.

The scratched casing.

The strip of masking tape:

SOLOMON.

A small red light appears.

REC.

Kai freezes.

The tape counter on the dead display changes.

00:00:00

to

00:00:01.

KAI
Malik.

Malik turns.

The red light is gone.

MALIK
What?

Kai picks up the camcorder.

Opens the battery compartment.

Empty.

He shows Malik.

Malik looks at the empty compartment.

Then at Kai.

ADE
What happened?

Kai looks toward the scratched photograph.

Back to the camcorder.

KAI
Nothing.

The word arrives too easily.

Bode hears it.

So does Malik.

For the first time—

Neither lets it pass.

CUT TO BLACK.

# SEQUENCE IV — THE WILL

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - DINING ROOM - MORNING

8:57.

The batteryless wall clock remains face-up on the counter.

Stopped.

Malik's watch is not.

He checks it.

Then the front window.

Then the watch again.

The dining table has been cleared of funeral food.

Four chairs on one side.

One chair opposite.

Five water glasses.

Five legal pads.

Five pens.

The scratched photograph remains at the centre.

Face-up.

A deliberate imperfection.

Ade enters wearing yesterday's black trousers and one of Solomon's cardigans.

Too short in the sleeves.

He carries two mugs.

ADE
I made coffee.

MALIK
There is coffee.

Ade looks at the full pot beside Malik.

ADE
Then I made competition.

He sets one mug in front of Kai.

Kai sits with the old camcorder open across his knees.

A fresh battery beside it.

The wrong battery.

He has tried anyway.

ADE
Any more messages from beyond?

KAI
It wasn't a message.

ADE
One second feels concise.

Malik looks at him.

Ade drinks.

The joke retreats.

Bode stands near the window.

Still in yesterday's charcoal trousers.

No jacket.

He studies the scratched photograph without touching it.

MALIK
You know the lawyer?

BODE
I know her name.

MALIK
Dad knew her.

BODE
Your father knew many people in
categories.

ADE
Family.

Lawyer.

People he disappointed internationally.

BODE
That category was very large.

Ade almost smiles.

This one lives.

The doorbell rings.

8:59.

Malik checks his watch.

Of course.

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - FOYER - MOMENTS LATER

Malik opens the door.

MAYA PATEL, 52, stands beneath a black umbrella.

Estate lawyer.

Precise without being brittle.

She carries a leather case and a narrow archival box sealed with red evidence tape.

PATEL
Malik?

MALIK
You're early.

PATEL
Your father trained me.

She closes the umbrella.

Sees Solomon's polished shoes beside the door.

A breath catches.

Professional discipline restores it.

PATEL (CONT'D)
I'm sorry.

MALIK
Thank you.

Neither pretends the phrase is enough.

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - DINING ROOM - MOMENTS LATER

Patel sits opposite the brothers.

Bode at the far end.

Patel opens her case.

Two certified documents.

A passport envelope.

A cemetery release form.

Four flight itineraries.

The sealed archival box.

Ade counts the documents.

ADE
He left homework.

PATEL
He left instructions.

ADE
That's what homework is when the teacher
is dead.

Patel looks at him.

Not offended.

PATEL
You must be Ade.

ADE
Was it the grief or the charm?

PATEL
Your father described you as
"constitutionally unable to let a room
remain uncomfortable."

Ade sits back.

The accuracy hurts.

PATEL looks to Kai.

PATEL (CONT'D)
And Kai.

Kai nods.

Her eyes settle on the camcorder.

PATEL (CONT'D)
He asked whether that still worked.

KAI
When?

PATEL
Six months ago.

KAI
What did you tell him?

PATEL
That I was an estate lawyer.

Kai waits.

PATEL (CONT'D)
He said that had never stopped me from
giving opinions before.

The smallest smile between them.

Then business.

Patel places a certified copy of the will on the table.

PATEL
Solomon signed his final will eighteen
months ago.

He amended the funeral instructions
twice after that.

Malik straightens.

MALIK
What amendments?

Patel looks at him.

Then Bode.

Bode knows nothing.

PATEL
We should begin with the part your father
made unnecessarily difficult.

ADE
That narrows it down.

PATEL
Solomon was cremated at four-ten
yesterday morning.

Silence.

Malik does not understand the sentence.

MALIK
No.

PATEL
The urn placed in the Mountain View
columbarium contains his cremated remains.

Malik looks toward the hallway.

Toward the absence of the urn.

MALIK
We lowered a casket.

PATEL
You lowered a ceremonial casket containing
personal effects he selected in advance.

Ade puts down his coffee.

ADE
We buried his things.

PATEL
Yes.

ADE
And put him in a wall.

PATEL
Yes.

ADE
Did that sentence sound normal at any
point during the paperwork?

PATEL
No.

The honesty silences him.

Malik opens the will.

Pages move too quickly beneath his hands.

MALIK
I signed the funeral authorization.

PATEL
You signed the authorization presented
to the next of kin.

The pre-need arrangements were already
binding.

MALIK
You let me bury an empty casket.

PATEL
I followed your father's written
instructions.

MALIK
You lied.

PATEL
I was instructed not to disclose the
cremation until nine o'clock this morning.

I advised him against that instruction.

In writing.

More than once.

Malik rises.

His chair remains perfectly aligned with the table.

MALIK
Why?

Patel opens the will to a marked page.

PATEL
Because the casket was intended to remain
in Vancouver.

And the urn was not.

Bode closes his eyes.

Not surprise.

Something closer to dread.

PATEL reads.

PATEL (CONT'D)
"I direct that my cremated remains be
carried to Cross River State, Nigeria,
by my sons Malik, Ade and Kai Oku."

Kai looks up.

PATEL (CONT'D)
"They are to travel together.

No representative may act in place of
any son.

My ashes are to be released by their
hands at the river boundary of the Oku
family land outside Calabar."

The word CALABAR changes the room.

Kai looks at the scratched photograph.

The white house.

The massive tree.

The missing woman.

PATEL (CONT'D)
"Only after this act is completed may
the accompanying Nigerian instrument
be presented for execution."

Malik turns a page.

MALIK
What instrument?

Patel removes the second certified document.

PATEL
The Canadian will does not transfer
Nigerian land.

Your father retained counsel in Calabar.

That office holds the local instrument
and title records.

Under those documents, the three of you
are the intended joint beneficiaries of
the Oku family house and surrounding land.

ADE
How much land?

PATEL
Enough that I will not estimate it from
a Vancouver file.

MALIK
Can it be sold?

Bode looks at him.

PATEL
Not through this estate.

And not before the Nigerian conditions
are addressed.

MALIK
So this is leverage.

PATEL
It is a condition.

MALIK
It is a dead man forcing three adults
onto an airplane.

PATEL
No.

She lets that settle.

PATEL (CONT'D)
If you refuse, you inherit no interest
in the Calabar property.

The property remains with the existing
family trust.

There is no debt.

No penalty.

Your father left you a choice.

BODE
He left them a deadline.

Patel looks to him.

PATEL
Thirty days from the date of death.

BODE
Then he left them a deadline.

Patel does not disagree.

Kai takes one of the itineraries.

VANCOUVER.

LAGOS.

CALABAR.

Departure:

FRIDAY.

Three days away.

KAI
He bought tickets.

PATEL
Four.

She gives the last itinerary to Bode.

Bode does not take it.

PATEL (CONT'D)
He named you escort and local liaison.

BODE
Without asking me.

PATEL
He prepaid the ticket.

BODE
That is not asking.

ADE
Apparently that's hereditary.

Patel slides the cemetery release form toward Malik.

His name is already printed beneath the authorization line.

MALIK
What's this?

PATEL
An application to remove the urn from
the columbarium.

Mountain View has the supporting order.

They are expecting your signature.

Malik stares at the line.

MALIK
He knew we'd put it there.

PATEL
He knew you would finish what was
in front of you.

The sentence finds the wound exactly.

Malik looks at Patel.

She does not look away.

PATEL (CONT'D)
I am not defending him.

I am explaining the mechanism.

Ade picks up his itinerary.

ADE
Friday.

MALIK
We're not going.

KAI
I'm going.

MALIK
No.

KAI
That wasn't a question.

Malik looks at him.

Something new between them.

Not rebellion.

Refusal.

ADE
Can everybody wait until the lawyer
leaves before we become a family again?

PATEL
I have seen families.

This is within range.

She opens the passport envelope.

Inside:

Solomon's Nigerian passport.

Expired.

A small brass KEY taped to the inside flap.

And a MiniDV CASSETTE.

Handwritten label:

WHEN YOU ARRIVE.

Kai reaches for the tape.

Patel covers it with one hand.

PATEL (CONT'D)
He directed that this remain sealed until
all three of you are inside the Calabar
house.

ADE
And if we watch it now?

PATEL
You will have ignored a dead man's
instruction.

Ade looks around.

ADE
Feels crowded in here already.

Patel seals the envelope again.

Places it beside the scratched photograph.

The photograph.

The key.

The tape.

Three forms of access.

Malik looks at the cemetery release.

The signature line.

The four itineraries.

Then his brothers.

MALIK
We vote.

ADE
Since when?

MALIK
Since he stopped getting one.

Kai raises his hand.

No hesitation.

Malik does not.

Ade looks between them.

Bode finally takes his itinerary.

Outside—

Rain begins again.

In the scratched photograph, water stains spread through the old Calabar sky.

Stopping just before the missing woman's face.

CUT TO BLACK.
